There's too much overlap.

01:16:10.643 --> 01:16:12.010
We've spoken to him.
He'll do it.

01:16:12.044 --> 01:16:14.712
For what, a dollar?
Why would I do that?

01:16:14.747 --> 01:16:16.381
I got
China Investment

01:16:16.415 --> 01:16:18.149
and Mitsubishi
kicking my tires.

01:16:18.184 --> 01:16:21.720
I know those guys. They're not
gonna close a deal in time.

01:16:21.754 --> 01:16:24.923
We want you
to call Jamie.

01:16:24.957 --> 01:16:26.758
Let me ask you
a question.

01:16:26.792 --> 01:16:29.761
35,000 jobs just
disappeared in this city

01:16:29.795 --> 01:16:31.963
between A.I.G.,
Lehman and Bear.

01:16:31.997 --> 01:16:33.465
We make a deal
with Jamie--

01:16:33.499 --> 01:16:36.534
he'll fire 20,000
Morgan Stanley employees.

01:16:36.569 --> 01:16:38.703
You think that's good
public policy?

01:16:38.737 --> 01:16:42.173
John, we are looking
at the whole system here.

01:16:42.207 --> 01:16:44.158
The Chinese are leaving.

01:16:44.183 --> 01:16:45.743
GAO found out we're also
talking to Mitsubishi.

01:16:45.744 --> 01:16:47.478
I gotta go.

01:16:47.513 --> 01:16:51.049
All right, get me Kuroyanagi
and a Japanese translator.

01:16:51.083 --> 01:16:53.084
We're closing with
Mitsubishi tonight.

01:16:53.119 --> 01:16:55.720
Tim Geithner's
calling again.

01:16:55.754 --> 01:16:57.257
Cover your ears.

01:16:57.282 --> 01:16:58.982
You tell Tim Geithner
to fucking blow me.

01:16:58.991 --> 01:17:01.158
I'm trying to save
my company.

01:17:03.661 --> 01:17:06.564
Put him on the schedule,
but make sure it's after lunch,

01:17:06.598 --> 01:17:09.667
because that way I can
fit Maddle in beforehand.

01:17:09.702 --> 01:17:12.671
Morgan just made a deal
with Mitsubishi.

01:17:12.706 --> 01:17:14.674
So we're
the only bank

01:17:14.708 --> 01:17:17.010
with our dick
still in the wind.

01:17:17.044 --> 01:17:20.247
I'm calling
Buffett again.

01:17:24.920 --> 01:17:27.288
Grandpa, they keep calling.
What if it's important?

01:17:27.323 --> 01:17:29.758
They always think
it's important.

01:17:32.062 --> 01:17:35.598
All right,
I'll make it fast.

01:17:37.001 --> 01:17:39.002
Warren, thanks for calling back.
How are you?

01:17:39.037 --> 01:17:41.037
Just fine, Lloyd.

01:17:41.072 --> 01:17:42.737
What can I do
for you today?

01:17:42.771 --> 01:17:45.437
I'd like to talk to you about
taking a stake in Goldman Sachs.

01:17:45.471 --> 01:17:48.104
<i>What do you have in mind?</i>
<i>Sounds expensive.</i>

01:17:48.139 --> 01:17:50.306
Maybe not.

01:17:52.074 --> 01:17:54.608
<i>You'd better have</i>
<i>good news,</i>

01:17:54.643 --> 01:17:56.908
<i>because I might be dead</i>
<i>before we finish</i>

01:17:56.943 --> 01:17:59.109
<i>haggling over TARP.</i>

01:17:59.144 --> 01:18:02.079
Buffett's throwing
$5 billion into Goldman.

01:18:05.116 --> 01:18:07.651
We're off the ledge.

01:18:07.685 --> 01:18:09.720
<i>For a moment.</i>

01:18:09.754 --> 01:18:12.355
The October surprise
arrived a little early

01:18:12.390 --> 01:18:15.125
with a game-changing jolt
to the White House race.

01:18:15.160 --> 01:18:17.094
Call it a master stroke

01:18:17.128 --> 01:18:19.129
or a desperate
Hail-Mary pass--

01:18:19.164 --> 01:18:22.400
McCain announced he would
suspend his campaign

01:18:22.434 --> 01:18:25.537
and asked for this Friday's
debate to be postponed

01:18:25.571 --> 01:18:28.807
So he can return to Washington
to focus on the economic crisis.

01:18:28.842 --> 01:18:31.977
Now is our chance
to come together,

01:18:32.012 --> 01:18:34.714
to prove that Washington
is once again

01:18:34.748 --> 01:18:37.917
capable of leading
this country.

01:18:37.951 --> 01:18:40.819
Thank God he came back.

01:18:40.854 --> 01:18:45.023
Like Daniel Day Lewis
in "Last of the Mohicans,"

01:18:45.057 --> 01:18:47.692
he will find us!

01:18:49.328 --> 01:18:51.562
- They're blowing it up.
- What happened?

01:18:51.596 --> 01:18:53.297
McCain wanted to swoop in
and save the day,

01:18:53.331 --> 01:18:54.932
but doesn't have any idea
how to do it.

01:18:54.966 --> 01:18:56.867
It's 100-page
piece of legislation

01:18:56.901 --> 01:18:58.935
we've been carefully
negotiating for days.

01:18:58.970 --> 01:19:01.138
What, did he think they were
gonna sit around and spitball?

01:19:01.172 --> 01:19:03.106
Yeah, when McCain
got here

01:19:03.141 --> 01:19:06.409
and found out that the deal
was basically done, he went apeshit.

01:19:06.444 --> 01:19:08.311
The Republicans fell in
behind their guy.

01:19:08.346 --> 01:19:10.046
They want to start
all over again.

01:19:10.081 --> 01:19:12.315
Democrats flipped out.
Republicans dug in.

01:19:12.350 --> 01:19:14.751
Clusterfuck.

01:19:14.785 --> 01:19:18.088
- Where's Hank?
- Still talking to McCain.

01:19:18.122 --> 01:19:20.523
If you or anyone else
does anything

01:19:20.558 --> 01:19:24.060
that causes a depression,
it is not gonna be on me.

01:19:24.095 --> 01:19:26.697
I have a big mouth, Senator--

01:19:26.722 --> 01:19:27.897
- a very big mouth.
- Hold on...

01:19:27.898 --> 01:19:30.333
He's not threatening

01:19:30.367 --> 01:19:32.801
the Republican
Presidential Nominee, is he?

01:19:32.836 --> 01:19:35.303
- Something's got to be done.
- No no. Excuse me, please.

01:19:35.338 --> 01:19:37.305
Where are the Democrats?

01:19:37.340 --> 01:19:39.141
They're right down
this way.

01:19:39.175 --> 01:19:40.709
- Is Nancy there?
- Yes. Yes, she is.

01:19:40.743 --> 01:19:42.044
Thank you.

01:19:49.752 --> 01:19:51.686
<i>Nancy...</i>

01:19:55.356 --> 01:19:57.624
Gee, Hank.

01:19:57.659 --> 01:19:59.559
I didn't know
you were Catholic.

01:20:01.194 --> 01:20:03.296
I beg of you, don't blow this up.
It was a bad meeting,

01:20:03.330 --> 01:20:05.364
but we need to get
together on this.

01:20:05.399 --> 01:20:07.367
We're not the ones
trying to blow it up.

01:20:07.401 --> 01:20:09.871
I just ask you
to stay with us.

01:20:11.974 --> 01:20:15.143
Please.

01:20:15.177 --> 01:20:16.978
The House began debating
the rescue bill

01:20:17.012 --> 01:20:18.479
at 9:27 this morning.

01:20:18.514 --> 01:20:21.282
<i>At about 1:28 pm</i>
<i>Congress did finally act.</i>

01:20:21.316 --> 01:20:23.618
- This is a squeaker of a vote.
- <i>We are down to it right now.</i>

01:20:23.652 --> 01:20:25.887
<i>It looks like the Democrats</i>
<i>delivered their caucus</i>

01:20:25.921 --> 01:20:28.089
<i>and the Republicans</i>
<i>so far have not.</i>

01:20:28.124 --> 01:20:30.325
<i>What do you think they could do</i>
<i>to change the bill</i>

01:20:30.359 --> 01:20:32.227
<i>to get a few Republican votes</i>
<i>over to the other side?</i>

01:20:32.261 --> 01:20:34.028
<i>If they hang</i>
<i>Wall Street CEOs,</i>

01:20:34.063 --> 01:20:35.463
<i>I think that would get</i>
<i>a few more votes.</i>

01:20:35.498 --> 01:20:37.265
<i>You know, I'm not--</i>
<i>I'm not sure</i>

01:20:37.299 --> 01:20:39.167
<i>what they could do</i>
<i>exactly.</i>

01:20:39.201 --> 01:20:42.570
<i>It is possible that the leadership</i>
<i>of the Congress would conclude</i>

01:20:42.605 --> 01:20:45.573
<i>that there's nothing that can</i>
<i>get a majority of support</i>

01:20:45.608 --> 01:20:48.342
<i>and see what Hank Paulson can do</i>
<i>and the administration can do--</i>

01:20:50.278 --> 01:20:52.312
<i>Leaders are negotiating</i>
<i>right now</i>

01:20:52.347 --> 01:20:54.548
<i>who'll risk their seats.</i>
<i>And that's what I'm hearing.</i>

01:20:54.582 --> 01:20:57.114
Pelosi wouldn't have brought
the bill to the floor if she

01:20:57.139 --> 01:20:58.316
didn't think it would pass.

01:20:58.317 --> 01:20:59.852
<i>I don't know the answer</i>
<i>to that, Charlie. I can't answer.</i>

01:20:59.922 --> 01:21:01.890
<i>I'm just reading an email</i>
<i>that's coming to me.</i>

01:21:01.924 --> 01:21:03.327
<i>I think the bottom line</i>

01:21:03.328 --> 01:21:04.435
<i>is they gotta go back</i>
<i>to the drawing board.</i>

01:21:04.460 --> 01:21:06.127
<i>Do they have the time</i>
<i>though to do that?</i>

01:21:06.161 --> 01:21:07.860
<i>Look at the Dow Jones</i>
<i>Industrial Average.</i>

01:21:07.894 --> 01:21:09.794
<i>Well, you know,</i>
<i>you're gonna get a--</i>

01:21:09.829 --> 01:21:10.939
<i>At this point we just</i>

01:21:10.964 --> 01:21:12.364
<i>gotta hold on to the sides</i>
<i>of the kayak</i>

01:21:12.365 --> 01:21:13.798
<i>and ride through this</i>
<i>because--</i>

01:21:13.831 --> 01:21:15.765
<i>They didn't pass it.</i>

01:21:15.799 --> 01:21:17.799
- <i>They did not pass it.</i>
- <i>It just wasn't enough.</i>

01:21:17.834 --> 01:21:22.002
<i>They're gonna end up being</i>
<i>nine votes short, Bill.</i>

01:21:22.037 --> 01:21:23.703
<i>Say that again, Steve.</i>

01:21:23.738 --> 01:21:25.638
<i>I think they're gonna end up</i>
<i>being nine votes--</i>

01:21:25.672 --> 01:21:27.906
<i>if they get all six--</i>
<i>five of the remaining votes,</i>

01:21:27.940 --> 01:21:31.808
<i>they'll be 10 votes short now--</i>
<i>if they get all five remaining.</i>

01:21:31.843 --> 01:21:33.543
<i>The writing is</i>
<i>on the wall there.</i>

01:21:33.577 --> 01:21:35.711
<i>And we're here</i>
<i>down on the floor.</i>

01:21:35.745 --> 01:21:38.079
<i>Traders have been standing around.</i>
<i>We're all here in knots.</i>

01:21:42.519 --> 01:21:45.991
The networks are waiting for you
in the press room.

01:21:46.025 --> 01:21:49.027
I can't even--

01:22:00.942 --> 01:22:02.943
We have to
go back again.

01:22:02.977 --> 01:22:05.446
They don't get
to say no on this.

01:22:06.347 --> 01:22:07.981
Okay.

01:22:08.016 --> 01:22:09.149
The White House
wants a meeting.

01:22:09.184 --> 01:22:11.151
Good. We'll come up
with a new strategy.

01:22:11.186 --> 01:22:13.220
The White House has to
push harder on the Hill.

01:22:13.255 --> 01:22:16.090
Meanwhile we need to keep working
on what we do with the money.

01:22:16.124 --> 01:22:17.591
Let's act like
this is gonna work.

01:22:17.626 --> 01:22:19.426
In that case, let's talk
about cash injections.

01:22:19.460 --> 01:22:20.672
Here we go again.

01:22:20.697 --> 01:22:22.028
We can't nationalize
the banks.

01:22:22.029 --> 01:22:23.101
It's not nationali--

01:22:23.126 --> 01:22:24.626
That's how Japan got itself
a decade-long recession.

01:22:24.697 --> 01:22:27.165
Is that where
we want to go?

01:22:27.199 --> 01:22:29.367
What else do we have?

01:22:29.401 --> 01:22:30.935
Cash-for-trash.

01:22:30.960 --> 01:22:32.860
Buying toxic assets
is still our go-to move.

01:22:33.638 --> 01:22:37.074
All right.
Find a way to simplify it.

01:22:37.108 --> 01:22:39.977
Dan, work something up.

01:22:40.011 --> 01:22:43.114
For discussion purposes,
let's see what it would look like.

01:22:54.027 --> 01:22:56.796
For those who supported the
$700 billion Wall Street bailout,

01:22:56.830 --> 01:22:59.031
it was a surprising
and stunning failure

01:22:59.066 --> 01:23:01.367
when the House of Representatives
voted to reject it.

01:23:01.401 --> 01:23:03.836
<i>It's a stinging defeat</i>
<i>for President Bush</i>

01:23:03.870 --> 01:23:06.573
<i>delivered at the hands</i>
<i>of his fellow Republicans.</i>

01:23:06.607 --> 01:23:10.042
We put forth a plan
that was big

01:23:10.077 --> 01:23:11.811
because we've got
a big problem.

01:23:11.845 --> 01:23:15.748
The reality is that we're
in an urgent situation.

01:23:15.783 --> 01:23:19.018
and the consequences
will grow worse each day

01:23:19.053 --> 01:23:20.486
if we do not act.

01:23:20.521 --> 01:23:21.988
I know.
I keep telling--

01:23:22.022 --> 01:23:23.489
draft of
the new bill.

01:23:23.524 --> 01:23:25.124
Are they having
any luck with it?

01:23:25.159 --> 01:23:27.694
The White House thinks they
got a better shot of pushing it

01:23:27.729 --> 01:23:30.297
through the Senate side first.
Hopefully they're right.

01:23:30.332 --> 01:23:32.266
They asked us to back off
and let them handle it.

01:23:32.300 --> 01:23:35.203
So I'm-- I'm--
I'm trying to back off.

01:23:40.242 --> 01:23:43.077
Buying toxic assets
isn't gonna work.

01:23:43.112 --> 01:23:44.678
Why not?

01:23:44.713 --> 01:23:46.246
It's too slow.

01:23:46.280 --> 01:23:47.714
I think I've been
saying that.

01:23:47.748 --> 01:23:49.715
Well, we knew it was complicated,
but how slow--?

01:23:49.749 --> 01:23:51.216
Two months,
maybe more.

01:23:51.251 --> 01:23:52.634
Oh.

01:23:52.659 --> 01:23:53.959
How is it possible
we didn't know how--?

01:23:54.020 --> 01:23:58.256
I didn't ask how long
it would take, okay?

01:23:58.290 --> 01:24:00.624
Can we move on?

01:24:00.659 --> 01:24:04.428
So maybe we can talk about
capital injections.

01:24:04.462 --> 01:24:06.330
Dan, we really can't.

01:24:06.364 --> 01:24:08.499
I think
we're gonna have to.

01:24:08.533 --> 01:24:11.035
Even if neel could
expedite the process,

01:24:11.069 --> 01:24:14.605
which seems unlikely,

01:24:14.639 --> 01:24:16.607
<i>the system</i>
<i>is crumbling.</i>

01:24:16.641 --> 01:24:19.343
<i>The banks need</i>
<i>money now.</i>

01:24:19.377 --> 01:24:22.880
If cash injections are the most
efficient way to stabilize them,

01:24:22.914 --> 01:24:26.049
then we can't back off

01:24:26.083 --> 01:24:28.051
because we're uncomfortable
being the men

01:24:28.085 --> 01:24:30.387
who nationalized
a few American banks.

01:24:30.421 --> 01:24:32.055
It's faster,
that's for sure.

01:24:32.089 --> 01:24:34.157
It will push us back
off the precipice, yes,

01:24:34.191 --> 01:24:37.760
unfreeze the system.

01:24:37.795 --> 01:24:40.530
We give them some money

01:24:40.564 --> 01:24:43.866
and they lend it out.

01:24:47.738 --> 01:24:49.205
The motion is adopted.

01:24:49.239 --> 01:24:51.574
After rejecting the Bush
Administration's T.A.R.P. Plan

01:24:51.608 --> 01:24:54.211
only four days ago,
the House passed it today.

01:24:54.245 --> 01:24:56.081
The big question now--

01:24:56.106 --> 01:24:57.906
whether investors will take
comfort in the news.

01:24:57.949 --> 01:24:59.916
<i>Current indicators show</i>
<i>the stock market</i>

01:24:59.951 --> 01:25:02.986
<i>is continuing</i>
<i>its freefall.</i>

01:25:21.340 --> 01:25:22.673
<i>Hello.</i>

01:25:22.707 --> 01:25:25.009
Warren, it's Hank.

01:25:25.043 --> 01:25:28.112
I-- I-- I'm sorry.
It's late.

01:25:28.146 --> 01:25:30.447
Am I waking you?

01:25:30.482 --> 01:25:32.917
<i>No, not at all.</i>

01:25:32.951 --> 01:25:35.085
Can I pick your brain
for a minute?

01:25:35.120 --> 01:25:37.888
<i>Sure.</i>
<i>What's the problem?</i>

01:25:37.922 --> 01:25:41.559
How do you get
a healthy bank

01:25:41.593 --> 01:25:44.461
to accept
a capital injection?

01:26:38.483 --> 01:26:40.951
I had to drag my ass all the
way here from California.

01:26:40.986 --> 01:26:42.887
They wouldn't even
tell my why.

01:26:42.921 --> 01:26:44.789
Nobody knows
what this is about?

01:26:44.823 --> 01:26:46.924
Nope.

01:26:52.097 --> 01:26:53.764
Talk to Jamie?

01:26:53.799 --> 01:26:56.034
Yep. He'll be fine.

01:26:56.068 --> 01:26:57.903
Did you tell him
what was coming?

01:26:57.937 --> 01:27:00.038
Uh, did I tell him we're about
to make him swallow

01:27:00.073 --> 01:27:03.409
a capital injection
he doesn't need? No.

01:27:03.443 --> 01:27:06.112
I-- I told him
we need his help

01:27:06.146 --> 01:27:09.583
and I asked him very politely
not to fuck with us today.

01:27:10.952 --> 01:27:12.286
He got it.

01:27:13.588 --> 01:27:15.656
She's here.

01:27:20.630 --> 01:27:22.598
Gentlemen.

01:27:22.632 --> 01:27:24.366
We think this is
gonna work?

01:27:24.401 --> 01:27:26.769
Oh yeah.
They're gonna love it.

01:27:48.895 --> 01:27:50.829
We are of the view

01:27:50.864 --> 01:27:52.831
that the United States
needs

01:27:52.866 --> 01:27:55.534
to take strong,
decisive action

01:27:55.568 --> 01:27:58.703
to arrest the stress

01:27:58.737 --> 01:28:02.239
in our financial system.

01:28:02.273 --> 01:28:05.308
Through our new
T.A.R.P. Authority,

01:28:05.342 --> 01:28:08.277
Treasury will purchase

01:28:08.311 --> 01:28:10.546
preferred stock

01:28:10.580 --> 01:28:13.514
in each of the banks
represented in this room.

01:28:15.850 --> 01:28:18.284
<i>That stock will yield 5%</i>
<i>the first five years,</i>

01:28:18.319 --> 01:28:21.253
<i>9% after that.</i>

01:28:21.287 --> 01:28:23.954
We give you money;
You lend it out.

01:28:23.989 --> 01:28:27.390
It will unfreeze credit,
stabilize the banks,

01:28:27.425 --> 01:28:29.292
restore confidence.

01:28:29.327 --> 01:28:31.394
<i>Everyone will be</i>
<i>better off</i>

01:28:31.428 --> 01:28:33.428
with more capital
in the system.

01:28:33.463 --> 01:28:35.496
And that is why

01:28:35.531 --> 01:28:39.366
all nine of you

01:28:39.401 --> 01:28:42.269
will participate
in the program.

01:28:45.740 --> 01:28:47.508
Some of us don't need
any capital.

01:28:47.542 --> 01:28:50.011
You all need capital.

01:28:50.045 --> 01:28:52.579
You have no idea what the
market's gonna look like in a year.

01:28:52.614 --> 01:28:54.681
Neither do you.

01:28:54.716 --> 01:28:56.683
I'm not one of you
New York guys

01:28:56.717 --> 01:28:58.652
with your
fancy products.

01:28:58.686 --> 01:29:01.555
Well, why am I in this room
talking about bailing you out?

01:29:01.589 --> 01:29:05.158
The stronger banks will serve
as cover for the weaker banks.

01:29:05.192 --> 01:29:07.794
If just some of you take it,
the money is a signal

01:29:07.828 --> 01:29:10.897
that a bank is too weak to survive.
The market will devour it.

01:29:10.931 --> 01:29:13.633
How much are we
talking about?

01:29:13.667 --> 01:29:16.603
$125 billion.

01:29:18.739 --> 01:29:20.707
<i>Bank of America--</i>
<i>$15 billion.</i>

01:29:20.741 --> 01:29:23.042
<i>Bank of New York Mellon--</i>
<i>$3 billion.</i>

01:29:23.077 --> 01:29:26.579
<i>Citigroup--</i>
<i>$25 billion.</i>

01:29:26.613 --> 01:29:29.916
<i>Goldman Sachs--</i>
<i>$10 billion.</i>

01:29:29.950 --> 01:29:33.252
<i>J.P. Morgan--</i>
<i>$25 billion.</i>

01:29:33.287 --> 01:29:35.521
<i>Merrill Lynch--</i>
<i>$10 billion.</i>

01:29:35.556 --> 01:29:38.057
<i>Morgan Stanley--</i>
<i>$10 billion.</i>

01:29:38.091 --> 01:29:41.227
<i>State Street--</i>
<i>$2 billion.</i>

01:29:41.261 --> 01:29:43.596
<i>Wells Fargo--</i>
<i>$25 billion.</i>

01:29:49.469 --> 01:29:53.105
What happened
to buying toxic assets?

01:29:53.139 --> 01:29:54.707
Wasn't that the idea?

01:29:54.741 --> 01:29:56.241
<i>It's too slow.</i>

01:29:56.276 --> 01:29:58.343
You'll be dead
before we sort it out.

01:29:58.378 --> 01:30:01.780
So we're just handing
the reins over to you?

01:30:01.814 --> 01:30:03.448
The deal's actually
pretty good.

01:30:03.482 --> 01:30:06.117
You turn your nose up at this now,
and we have to rescue you later--

01:30:06.152 --> 01:30:07.919
the terms won't be
nearly as attractive.

01:30:07.953 --> 01:30:10.588
It's cheap capital.
It's not the worst idea in the world.

01:30:10.623 --> 01:30:12.557
Well, it is for those of us
who already have capital.

01:30:12.591 --> 01:30:14.692
We will be nonvoting
shareholders.

01:30:14.727 --> 01:30:17.228
This will be
a temporary measure.

01:30:19.665 --> 01:30:21.799
What if we decline
to be involved?

01:30:21.833 --> 01:30:25.369
The Chairman of the FDIC
is sitting right there.

01:30:25.404 --> 01:30:27.071
<i>Tomorrow you'll</i>
<i>find out</i>

01:30:27.105 --> 01:30:29.473
<i>that you're not as well-capitalized</i>
<i>as you think you are.</i>

01:30:29.508 --> 01:30:31.475
What kind of protections
can you offer on changes

01:30:31.510 --> 01:30:33.110
for compensation policy?

01:30:33.144 --> 01:30:35.980
I mean, if the government
is going to become a part-owner,

01:30:36.014 --> 01:30:37.982
does that mean
that the government

01:30:38.016 --> 01:30:40.551
is going to dictate
compensation?

01:30:40.585 --> 01:30:42.786
Are you asking me about your
bonus right now, John?

01:30:42.821 --> 01:30:45.155
I'm running
a company.

01:30:45.190 --> 01:30:47.157
If the Fed tells me
I can't offer

01:30:47.192 --> 01:30:49.460
competitive pay
for talent,

01:30:49.494 --> 01:30:52.662
you're gonna launch the biggest brain
drain this country's ever seen.

01:30:52.697 --> 01:30:54.530
Is that the way you want
to run the banks?

01:30:54.565 --> 01:30:56.565
Until the money is repaid
to the Treasury,

01:30:56.600 --> 01:31:00.035
there will be some limitations on tax
deductions and golden parachutes.

01:31:00.069 --> 01:31:02.103
- Well, there you go.
- I don't really understand

01:31:02.137 --> 01:31:04.738
why there needs to be
so much tension about this.

01:31:04.772 --> 01:31:06.706
The country is facing

01:31:06.741 --> 01:31:09.242
the worst economy
since the Great Depression.

01:31:09.276 --> 01:31:11.744
If the financial system
collapses,

01:31:11.778 --> 01:31:14.680
it will take
every one of you down.

01:31:22.887 --> 01:31:25.088
Give me the papers.

01:31:32.461 --> 01:31:34.095
- You can't just sign it.
- Oh no?

01:31:34.129 --> 01:31:37.764
- Not without your board.
- My board's on 24-hour notice.

01:31:37.798 --> 01:31:40.032
I think they'll
go along with it.

01:31:40.067 --> 01:31:44.669
And if they don't,
they'll fire me.

01:31:50.111 --> 01:31:52.879
Anyone else?

01:31:57.954 --> 01:32:00.222
Are they gonna do it?

01:32:01.491 --> 01:32:03.125
They're calling
their boards.

01:32:03.160 --> 01:32:05.628
- That's a good sign.
- If they do go along with this,

01:32:05.663 --> 01:32:08.331
we should announce
something alongside the injections--

01:32:08.366 --> 01:32:11.402
maybe a program
to buy up mortgages.

01:32:11.436 --> 01:32:13.137
I'm not rushing out
some half-assed plan

01:32:13.172 --> 01:32:14.940
just to make it look like
we're doing something.

01:32:14.974 --> 01:32:17.376
Maybe we just beef up
the restrictions

01:32:17.411 --> 01:32:20.147
on how they
spend the money--

01:32:20.181 --> 01:32:21.983
something to take
the stink off.

01:32:22.017 --> 01:32:24.686
Put more restrictions on it--
they won't take it.

01:32:29.292 --> 01:32:31.628
One thing too many
for today.

01:32:33.799 --> 01:32:35.733
They almost bring down

01:32:35.768 --> 01:32:37.569
the U.S. economy
as we know it,

01:32:37.603 --> 01:32:40.071
but we can't put restrictions
on how they spend

01:32:40.105 --> 01:32:43.308
the $125 billion
we're giving them,

01:32:43.342 --> 01:32:47.545
because they might not
take it.

01:33:19.077 --> 01:33:21.311
What's this?

01:33:21.345 --> 01:33:25.148
That is, um...

01:33:25.182 --> 01:33:27.684
A poison dart frog.

01:33:27.718 --> 01:33:31.054
Wendy took it
in Guyana.

01:33:43.467 --> 01:33:46.069
Is this yours?

01:33:50.808 --> 01:33:53.142
Al Capone's.

01:33:55.245 --> 01:33:56.746
Eight out of the nine
are in.

01:33:56.780 --> 01:33:58.781
B of A is still waiting
on its board, but--

01:33:58.816 --> 01:34:01.317
it's gonna go through.

01:34:01.352 --> 01:34:03.953
<i>I'll call the Speaker's</i>
<i>office.</i>

01:34:03.987 --> 01:34:06.989
And we're gonna get you
on the phone with the President.

01:34:07.024 --> 01:34:09.826
<i>Okay.</i>

01:34:12.763 --> 01:34:15.564
Dow is up 900 points

01:34:15.599 --> 01:34:17.967
just because
we were meeting.

01:34:20.270 --> 01:34:24.274
<i>Well, that's good.</i>

01:34:24.308 --> 01:34:26.843
That's good.

01:34:26.877 --> 01:34:29.578
It was the right thing.

01:34:29.612 --> 01:34:32.515
<i>Absolutely.</i>

01:34:32.549 --> 01:34:34.483
I was prepared
for more blowback.

01:34:34.518 --> 01:34:37.586
They didn't have
a choice.

01:34:37.621 --> 01:34:39.989
They knew that.

01:34:41.458 --> 01:34:46.195
Well, I certainly hope
that they--

01:34:46.230 --> 01:34:47.497
What?

01:34:49.366 --> 01:34:53.569
I hope they use the money
the way we're asking them to.

01:34:53.604 --> 01:34:58.541
They will lend it out,
won't they?

01:34:59.776 --> 01:35:02.478
Of course they will.

01:35:13.957 --> 01:35:16.458
Of course they will.

